        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
  Our observations focus on the continuum emission. Gas is not expected in debris disks as old as our targets (few Gyr) and with the low
  collisional excitation expected for these disks. However, its presence would reduce collisional velocities and provide another explanation
  for the unusual size distribution observed. Thus, we optimize our observations for high sensitivity to continuum emission but also allowing
  for the detection of possible CO in the disk (one baseband centered on the 12CO 2-1 line with low but sufficient spectral resolution
  and maximum bandwidth). Spectrally resolving a potential gas line is not a goal of the proposed observations. This is the standard approach
  of debris disk observations where no gas is expected to be present but cannot be ruled out completely.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
  Angular resolution: We intend to measure the extend of the disks (smaller than but similar to 6" in radius). Measuring the radial width of the
  ring is not a critical for our science goals. Thus, the lowest angular resolution (most compact array) is sufficient and actually necessary to
  reach a high sensitivity to surface brightness (see sensitivity justification). Band 6 is used based on sensitivity arguments (see sensitivity
  justification). This results in an angular resolution of ~1.5".

  Largest angular scale: The larges angular scale of our selected configuration is 11". This is only slightly smaller than the upper limit on the
  diameter of the disks. Much smaller sub structure (i.e., the small radial width of the ring) is present, ensuring that spatial filtering is not an
  issue.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
  Continuum sensitivity: We intend to image dust rings in two debris disk (one in each science goal). We require to detect the predicted disk
  surface brightness (44uJy/beam in band 6 and the most compact configuration, FWHM = 1.5") with 5 sigma significance, which transforms
  into an RMS of 8.8uJy/beam. Details on our prediction of the surface brightness are given below and in the corresponding section of the
  immediate objective of the science case. Using the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator, we compute a total integration time of 3.5 hours and a total
  execution time of 5.9 hours.

  Spectral line RMS: Gas is not expected in debris disks as old as our targets (few Gyr) and with the low collisional excitation expected for
  these disks. However, its presence would reduce collisional velocities and provide another explanation for the unusual size distribution
  observed. Thus, we optimize our observations for high sensitivity to continuum emission but also allowing for the detection of possible
  CO in the disk (one baseband centered on the 12CO 2-1 line with low but sufficient spectral resolution and maximum bandwidth). This is
  the standard approach for debris disk observations and will not result in any loss of sensitivity to continuum emission.

  Prediction of continuum surface brightness: We used our available Herschel data to predict the extent and surface brightness of the
  target assuming it is a debris disk. Therefore, we estimated the total flux of the disk at ALMA wavelengths from a blackbody fit (considering
  the spatial constraints from the Herschel images, i.e., a disk radius &lt; 6") to the relevant Herschel fluxes (larger than or equal to 100 micron).
  The use of a blackbody instead of a modified blackbody in the present case is well justified by the nature of the dust present (large,
  blackbody like grains instead of smaller grains). In the case of HIP92043 (another cold disk candidate not proposed here as it is predicted
  to be too faint for the proposed observations), an additional data point from a marginal detection with APEX/LABOCA at 870 micron is available.
  This flux is consistent with - although by a factor of four higher than - the predicted flux from our blackbody fit (Fig. 1), which suggests that the
  actual flux of all candidates at ALMA wavelengths might be larger than predicted. In addition, we assumed the disks to be narrow rings with a
  radial extent smaller than the angular resolution of our proposed observations (ring width &lt; radius / 4). This assumption is reasonable, since the
  disks must be very far from the star to be as cold as observed, but also close enough to be unresolved by Herschel/PACS at 160 micron, which
  leaves only a narrow range of radial distances from the star. Furthermore, the angular resolution of our proposed observations will be relatively
  low (band 6, most compact configuration). Note that the extent of the cold disk is an upper limit which transforms into a lower limit of the surface
  brightness derived. Finally, we estimated the flux per beam by dividing the total flux by the number of beams needed to cover the whole
  circumference of the ring. This gives a good lower limit (but probably close to the real value) of the flux per beam, which we require to be
  detected at 5 sigma confidence, sufficient to achieve our science goals.

  Considering different wavelengths and array configurations, we find band 6 and the most compact configuration to be ideal to achieve our goals
  in the shortest time possible due to the large beam surface covering a large region of the disk and thus accumulating more surface brightness
  per beam (interferometrically speaking, this results in observations at the lowest spatial frequencies, at which extended structures produce high
  coherent flux). See Fig. 2 for a corresponding CASA simulation on the example of HIP27887 to support our estimates.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
