    <prp:abstract>
We intend to clarify the nature of the Herschel-discovered cold debris disks, one of the most intriguing discoveries of the Herschel debris disk programs. They represent cases where planet(esimal) formation took place, but did not produce bodies larger than few kilometers in the outer regions of the systems, so that they remained unstirred. We intend to observe the two brightest disks visible from Chajnantor. Both stars also harbor planets in the innermost regions which is not in contradiction to the cold disk hypothesis. Form these two most unusual planetary systems we will learn both in which regions of the systems planet formation succeeded and where it failed.

However, given the limited angular resolution of Herschel, each single cold disk can also be explained by a background galaxy (but this is highly unlikely to explain all detections together). Testing the cold disk hypothesis through spatially resolved imaging with ALMA is crucial for further studies. If a source was found to be a galaxy aligned with the star, its emission would peak well beyond 0.1mm, implying a very distant star forming galaxy (redshift well beyond unity). This would be an exciting result on its own.
</prp:abstract>
